  <h3>Cold War: Polarization and Globalization</h3>

  <h4>USSR: «Begins and Wins»</h4>

  <p>«Kozakevich’’s Gesture» at the 1980 summer Olympic games in Moscow: an emotional reaction to his victory, or a demonstration of a political position? Wladyslaw Kozakiewicz was a Polish athlete, Olympic champion and world record holder, who succeeded in vanquishing his Soviet opponent in the pole vault competition. The demonstration of his offensive gesture in Moscow in front of the eyes of the world public resonated in the press and was considered a protest against the socialist regime. The scandal reached such a height that the USSR’s representative in Poland attempted to remove the athlete’s medal. Polish authorities defended Kozakiewicz, however, explaining his gesture as a brain spasm, or an expression of joy.</p>

  <p>The USSR prepared rigorously to enter the worldwide sports arena and conquer it. In 1948 the USSR sent a delegation to observe the London games, and the state then declared its future participation in the Olympics. In 1951 the National Olympic Committee of the USSR was officially created and recognized by the International Olympic Committee.</p>

  <p>The confrontation between the USA and the USSR became the major focus of the Olympic games. The USSR first competed in the Olympics in the summer Helsinki games, and succeeded in sharing first place for total medals won with the USA. In the Olympiads between 1952 and 1980 the USSR dominated in the total number of medals won--with the exception of two games, in which the USA succeeded in surpassing its global rival.</p>

  <h4>Participation as Declaration</h4>

